---
const categories = [
  {
    name: "General",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "What is ReformLab?",
        a: "An open-source platform for policy impact analysis. It connects European open data to policy simulation models and produces distributional results — who benefits, who loses, how the targeting works — without requiring users to code or build data pipelines from scratch."
      },
      {
        q: "Who is it for?",
        a: "Three primary audiences: policy analysts in government who need to assess impact without building custom pipelines; researchers and economists who need reproducible microsimulation results; and evaluation teams who want to iterate on scenarios without outsourcing every assessment."
      },
      {
        q: "What kinds of policies can it model?",
        a: "Carbon taxes with various redistribution mechanisms, energy renovation subsidies, vehicle and appliance feebates, targeted social transfers, and any policy expressible as a parameter overlay on OpenFisca tax-benefit calculations. The template system is extensible."
      },
      {
        q: "Is it free?",
        a: "Yes. ReformLab is open-source. Free to use, free to modify, free to contribute to."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    name: "Data & Privacy",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "What data does it use?",
        a: "By default, ReformLab works entirely with publicly available data: INSEE published tables, Eurostat aggregates, EU-SILC public-use files, emission factor databases. No restricted microdata is required for any core workflow."
      },
      {
        q: "Can I use my own (restricted) data?",
        a: "Yes. The platform can ingest custom datasets. When you supply restricted microdata, it stays on your machine — the platform never copies, transmits, or persists your data beyond your local environment."
      },
      {
        q: "How are synthetic populations generated?",
        a: "From published marginal distributions using established statistical methods (iterative proportional fitting, combinatorial optimization). The generation process is fully documented: which source tables, which demographic targets, what tolerances were applied. No hidden defaults."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    name: "Technical",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "What's the relationship with OpenFisca?",
        a: "OpenFisca is the tax-benefit computation engine that ReformLab builds on. OpenFisca encodes legislation and computes individual/household-level effects. ReformLab provides everything above that: data preparation, scenario management, multi-year orchestration, vintage tracking, indicators, and user interfaces. OpenFisca is the engine; ReformLab is the car."
      },
      {
        q: "Do I need to know Python?",
        a: "No. The no-code GUI lets you select data, configure scenarios, run simulations, and view results entirely in the browser. Python is available for users who want full programmability, but it's not required."
      },
      {
        q: "Does it work offline?",
        a: "Yes. All computation runs locally. No network calls, no cloud dependencies. The platform runs on a standard laptop with 16GB RAM."
      },
      {
        q: "How large a population can it handle?",
        a: "MVP targets up to 500,000 households on a 16GB laptop. Core computations are vectorized (NumPy/Arrow), so 100k+ households complete in seconds."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    name: "Reproducibility",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "What is a run manifest?",
        a: "An automatically generated record of everything about a simulation run: engine version, dependency versions, input data hashes, all policy parameters, all synthetic population assumptions, timestamp. It's created as a side effect of running any simulation — no manual documentation needed."
      },
      {
        q: "Can I reproduce someone else's results?",
        a: "Yes, if they share their run manifest and scenario configuration. Install ReformLab, load their manifest, run it — you get identical results. Deterministic execution means same inputs always produce same outputs."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    name: "Comparison",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "How is this different from PolicyEngine?",
        a: "PolicyEngine is a web-native policy calculator focused on the US and UK. ReformLab focuses on continental Europe (starting with France), supports environmental policy templates beyond tax-benefit, includes multi-year dynamic projections with vintage tracking, and provides both a no-code GUI and a full Python API."
      },
      {
        q: "Why not just use OpenFisca directly?",
        a: "You can. OpenFisca is an excellent computation engine. But using it for a complete policy assessment means building your own data pipeline, scenario management, multi-year orchestration, indicators, and methodology documentation. ReformLab is the product layer that does all of this for you."
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<section id="faq" class="relative bg-surface-dark text-paper py-24 lg:py-32">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-8">
    <div class="reveal mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6">
        <div class="h-px w-12 bg-cta"></div>
        <span class="text-cta font-medium text-sm tracking-widest uppercase">FAQ</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="font-sans text-4xl lg:text-5xl font-bold text-paper leading-tight">
        Questions
      </h2>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-12">
      {categories.map((cat) => (
        <div class="reveal">
          <h3 class="font-sans text-xl font-semibold text-emerald-500/80 mb-6">{cat.name}</h3>
          <div class="space-y-3">
            {cat.questions.map((item) => (
              <details class="group rounded-lg border border-slate/20 overflow-hidden hover:border-slate/30 transition-colors duration-200">
                <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-5 cursor-pointer">
                  <span class="text-paper font-medium pr-6">{item.q}</span>
                  <svg class="w-4 h-4 text-slate-mid flex-shrink-0 transition-transform duration-300 group-open:rotate-45" viewBox="0 0 16 16" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                    <path d="M 8 2 v 12 M 2 8 h 12"/>
                  </svg>
                </summary>
                <div class="px-5 pb-5 -mt-1">
                  <p class="text-slate-light leading-relaxed">{item.a}</p>
                </div>
              </details>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
